title: For Sale:  SOLD AR57 carbine or upper receiver
postcontent: SOLD  AR 57 rifle with the 2nd generation upper. Chambered in the 5.7x28mm this cartridge offers mild report and virtually nonexistant recoil for fast and controllable follow up shots. And there are a lot of follow up shots available with this gun, the cartridge feeds from a top-loading 50 round FN P90 magazine, and ejects straight down through the lower receiver magazine well. The brass lands in a nice little pile, or you can make a brass catcher with a standard AR15 magazine with the spring and follower removed. In excellent condition with about 200 rounds fired. The Gen 2 upper has some nice refinements over the 1st gen, weighing over a pound less with unnecesary material removed from the picatinney handguards and a fluted barrel. Magazine release on the Gen 2 is ambidexterous, and it also has the option for left side charging, which I currently have set it up for for ease and speed of use. Ergo grip pistol grip and Magpul Moe adjustable stock included with the lower.To utilize left side charging the bolt hold open device is normally removed, however I wanted to be able to manually lock the bolt open. Instead of removing it I modified the BHO to clear the charging handle and the upper receiver so it could manually hold the bolt open. If you put the AR57 upper on an unmodified stock lower, the design of the upper prevents the BHO from being pressed in to lock the bolt open. Not a huge loss of function, as the PS90 magazines have no provision for tripping a LRBHO but I wanted to be able to manually lock the bolt back for chamber checks, malfunction clearance, and cease fires. I machined enough material from the BHO to allow it to clear the walls of the upper receiver so that it can now hold the bolt open. With this setup on the left side I have the ability to pull back and lock the bolt open with my left hand while keeping my right hand on the pistol grip. This is much less awkward than having to release my right hand from the pistol grip to pull the charging handle on the right side while activating the BHO with my left handThe bolt is a standard semi auto type. The buffer is a couple ounces heavier than the standard AR57 bolt, it slows the extraction resulting in slightly less deformed brass and adds a small extra margin of safety for the blowback design as well as slightly reduced recoil impulse for the already low recoil of the 5.7.It's currently wearing a truglow 2x red dot sight. I found the size and height is perfect for the short length raised Picatinney rail on the upper, while the low magnification red dot is very fast on target and about optimal for the 200 yard effective range of the 5.7x28. I've also tried a compact 3-9 power scope on it and found it's extremely accurate with sub-MOA groups being easy to attain. Long scopes that hang over the magazine impede loading and unloading but it can be done by swinging the magazine under the scope, it's just slow and awkward.I have several factory AR57 magazines and an ATI magazine. The AR57 mags are the way to go, they're affordable, feeding is flawless and the mags lock in and remove easily. Perfect copies of the FN mag but cost a lot less. The ATI mag doesnt lock in as easily though it does feed alright. The promag and korean aftermarkets I havnt tried but the manufacturer doesnt recommend them.The lower is an Omni Polymer lower, very lightweight and durable and lockup with the AR57 upper is nice and night. I've put some 200 rounds through this setup and it has very little wear. Asking $950 for the rifle, or $800 for the upper, optic not included. I'll include 4 AR57 factory magazines and 1 ATI magazine. Additional factory AR57 magazines are available for $20 each. 5.7 ammo available as well. If the optic is wanted I'd like $50 for that.
